author: @kellyw976
text:
(Please note: this is a very, very long comment, like an essay. If you're not in the mood to read a long comment then please feel free to skip it. Thank you! )

I grew up in the '80s and watched the entire original Transformers series and then some. Admittedly, I didn't watch most of the other Transformers movies or the other series that came later, and here are my thoughts on this movie, which I watched recently. It had a lot of really great things going for it, but also some things that really could have been done so much better. I loved the humor, there were parts where I had to pause the movie just to get all the laughter out of my system. It was a really cool idea to have Optimus Prime and Megatron start out as best friends, and I loved the way Starscream and the others were introduced, and Elita One and Bumblebee's central roles. (This is very nerdy, but Bumblebee was my first crush, I was maybe five or six at the time? Haha. So that's very nerdy but he'll always be special to me for this reason, and they portrayed him so wonderfully in this film). I thought the way the rivalry and general dynamic between D-16/Megatron and Starscream was introduced was excellent, and I loved how they depicted the way that Megatron's cannon made its first appearance, that was so well done. But some things... could have been done so much better considering the richness and quality of the story overall.

Please note: the following couple of paragraphs contain criticisms that I have of this movie (including SPOILERS); however, I want to emphasize again that I enjoyed it overall and thought there were some amazing things about it; maybe because I had found it to be very good I held it up to very high standards, and so I was disappointed where I felt it could have done better. If you feel that you will not be happy reading criticisms of this movie then, again, please feel free to stop reading here.

I feel like they kind of rushed into some things because they really wanted to get to a certain point in the plot, and they didn't allow enough time for certain dynamics and emotions to feel believable. For example, I feel like the transition from Orion Pax and D-16 going from best friends to enemies happened too fast and didn't feel credible; really, the change in personality in D-16 didn't feel credible in the short amount of time it was granted, even considering his motive. It just didn't feel convincing. Or like how quickly Starscream's followers relinquished their loyalty to him and rapidly switched to D-16 instead, it happened too quickly to feel credible. And especially the part toward the end where Orion Pax actually took a hit for Sentinel Prime - I felt like this was going too far, like I get that Orion would be against wanting to destroy and kill (like D-16 wanted), but actually standing in the line of fire to take a hit for Sentinel Prime, it felt like too much. I feel like taking a hit/risking your life is more something very personal that you would do for someone you deeply care about and love, it didn't feel like it fit for that situation. Especially since afterward Orion apparently had no qualms blasting D-16/Megatron with his hardest hit. You might say "oh but D-16 betrayed him by throwing him down (which also didn't feel like something he would credibly do), so supposedly that would justify why later in their fight Orion had blasted D-16 so readily - but it didn't have a feel of him hurting from a deep betrayal, which would show more conflict in him, an inner battle of love for his former best friend and the pain that the betrayal carried. Like Orion actually risked his life for Sentinel Prime but then not long after he easily blasted his former best friend with his most powerful hit... it just didn't feel believable to me. The writers could have done so much better.

Also I feel like the part where D-16 just let Orion fall into the abyss after he took the hit, that also didn't feel credible to me: like this person had been your best friend for such a long time, and then without any qualms you'd just let him fall to his doom, it was too much. He should have been shown to go through more conflict and turmoil, like even as angry as he felt, he wouldn't be able to just drop him. I felt like the writers were so eager to get to the point of an established rivalry between Optimus Prime and Megatron that they made everything go too fast to where it wasn't believable. Also like... I get that the original Transformers was intended for boys (even if I was a female who liked it as a kid and as an adult), and so most of the important characters were male-- but it still feels kind of crappy that even though Elita-1 is important in this film (one of the only two important females...) she still for some reason voluntarily takes second seat to Orion Pax and fangirls about his glory, where her greatest accomplishment is being second to him-- even though that doesn't make sense either if presumably she started out being ahead of him. But I get that if they did this differently, then fanboys would complain that they're "changing it to make it 'woke' and give females importance where it wasn't there originally," like how they complained about four female Ghostbusters - instead of saying that the original should have given females more importance in the first place, considering that we also liked watching it). Same with Airacnid: if she is so amazing then why is she so eagerly serving Sentinel Prime instead of being the important leader herself...

And speaking of which, I feel like Orion/Optimus' personality also changed a little too fast, from kind of a good-hearted rascal to this big commanding leader. It would have been more realistic to have him and Megatron both feel more conflicted about the relationship between them, and maybe fumble around with the new power of being a leader-- maybe feel that the responsibility was too heavy all at once, since neither of them really had prior experience leading... The way the ending was done was a little corny, I just feel like the writers were so eager to get to this point of "and this is how dynamics were in the original Transformers series, and now you saw how it became that way" - that they rushed toward it and then made some kind of cheesy scenes in the end of "I am Optimus Prime" etc. Was it still a good movie? Yes, I liked it and enjoyed watching it a lot, it had a lot of fantastic things going for it. I was really hoping that at the very end there would be some hilarious scene where Bumblebee does something stupid and it makes his horns pop out, but unfortunately that never happened - but they did include a funny scene with Bumblebee at the end, so that was cool.
